This should lead to performance-based funding, or budgeting to create an environment of quasi-markets. This will address the inherent lack of competition and competitiveness in Kenyan universities.
This is done by introducing paradigm shifts in our institutions, such that funding is based on a formula driven by directives, which are tied to inputs, outputs and performance indicators.
Suggested financing solutions include the introduction of deregulation of fees to reflect the per capita cost of education to the extent possible as the students move up the ladder, education loans, human capital contracts that work by students committing a part of their future income for financing their education, income contingent loans, graduate taxes and educational vouchers. 



